\ts\*

\c 1
\p
\v 1 On the first day of the second month of the year after the Israelite people had left Egypt, Yahweh spoke to Moses in the sacred tent while in the desert wilderness around Sinai. Yahweh told him,
\v 2 “Count the men among the whole Israelite community by their tribal groups and ancestral families. List by name all of the men, one by one.
\v 3 {More specifically, list} the men who are at least 20 years old and can be soldiers. Count them with Aaron by their army divisions.
\ts\*
\v 4 One man from each tribe will help you {and Aaron do this}. These men will lead their ancestral families.
\v 5 Their names are: Shedeur’s son Elizur, who is from {the tribe of} Reuben,
\v 6 Zurishaddai’s son Shelumiel, who is from {the tribe of} Simeon,

\ts\*
\v 7 Amminadab’s son Nahshon, who is from {the tribe of} Judah,
\v 8 Zuar’s son Nethanel, who is from {the tribe of} Issachar,
\v 9 Helon’s son Eliab, who is from {the tribe of} Zebulun,
\ts\*
\v 10 Ammihud’s son Elishama, who is from {the tribe of} Joseph’s son Ephraim, Pedahzur’s son Gamaliel, who is from {the tribe of} Joseph’s son Manasseh,
\v 11 Gideoni’s son Abidan, who is from {the tribe of} Benjamin,
\ts\*
\v 12 Ammishaddai’s son Ahiezer, who is from {the tribe of} Dan,
\v 13 Okran’s son Pagiel, who is from {the tribe of} Asher,
\v 14 Deuel’s son Eliasaph, who is from {the tribe of} Gad,
\v 15 {and} Enan’s son Ahira, who is from {the tribe of} Naphtali.”
\ts\*
\v 16 These men were those from the community whom Yahweh chose to lead their ancestral tribes. They led the Israelite tribal groups.
\ts\*
\v 17 Moses and Aaron summoned these men whom Yahweh had chosen by name.
\v 18 Moses and Aaron gathered the whole Israelite community on that same day. Then the men who were at least 20 years old registered themselves by name, one by one, according to their tribal groups, and their ancestral families.
\v 19 Moses did exactly what Yahweh ordered him {to do}. He counted these men in the desert wilderness around Sinai.
\ts\*
\p
\v 44 Moses and Aaron counted {all} these men. The 12 Israelite leaders, one from each ancestral family, helped them count {the men}.
\v 45 These men were all the Israelites whom Moses, Aaron, and the 12 leaders counted by their ancestral families. {These were the men} who were at least 20 years old and could be soldiers.
\v 46 They counted 603, 550 men in total.
\ts\*
\v 47 However, they did not count the Levites by their ancestral tribe along with the other tribes.
\p
\v 48 {This is} because Yahweh told Moses,
\v 49 “Do not count those who descended from Levi. Do not list them along with the {other} Israelites.
\ts\*
\v 50 Moses, order the Levites to manage the sacred tent where the Ten Commandments are and every object in it. They alone must transport the sacred tent and every object in it. They alone must take care of it and pitch their tents around it.
\v 51 The Levites must disassemble the sacred tent when the Israelites journey to another location, and the Levites must reconstruct it when the Israelites stay in a location. If anyone who is not a Levite approaches the sacred tent, the Levites must execute that person.
\v 52 Israelites must set up their tents at their own campsites with their own tribal flags. {They must set up their tents} by their army divisions.
\ts\*
\v 53 The Levites will set up their tents around the sacred tent where the Ten Commandments are, so that Yahweh does not become angry with the Israelite community. The Levites surely must take care of the sacred tent where the Ten Commandments are.”
\v 54 So the Israelites did exactly everything that Yahweh had ordered Moses {to tell them to do}.
\ts\*
\v 20-21 Moses and Aaron counted 46, 500 men who were at least 20 years old, could be soldiers, and had descended from Reuben, who was Jacob’s oldest son. They listed the names of these men by their tribal groups and ancestral families, one by one.
\v 22-23 Moses and Aaron counted 59, 300 men who were at least 20 years old, could be soldiers, and had descended from Simeon. They listed the names of these men by their tribal groups and ancestral families, one by one.
\ts\*
\p
\v 24-25 Moses and Aaron counted 45, 650 men who were at least 20 years old, could be soldiers, and had descended from Gad. They listed their names by their tribal groups and ancestral families.
\ts\*
\p
\v 26-27 Moses and Aaron counted 74, 600 men who were at least 20 years old, could be soldiers, and had descended from Judah. They listed their names by their tribal groups and ancestral families.
\ts\*
\p
\v 28-29 Moses and Aaron counted 54, 400 men who were at least 20 years old, could be soldiers, and had descended from Issachar. They listed their names by their tribal groups and ancestral families.
\ts\*
\p
\v 30-31 Moses and Aaron counted 57, 400 men who were at least 20 years old, could be soldiers, and had descended from Zebulun. They listed their names by their tribal groups and ancestral families.
\ts\*
\p
\v 32-33 Moses and Aaron counted 40, 500 men who were at least 20 years old, could be soldiers, and had descended from Joseph’s son Ephraim. They listed their names by their tribal groups and ancestral families.
\ts\*
\p
\v 34-35 Moses and Aaron counted 32, 200 men who were at least 20 years old, could be soldiers, and had descended from {Joseph’s son} Manasseh. They listed their names by their tribal groups and ancestral families.
\ts\*
\p
\v 36-37 Moses and Aaron counted 35, 400 men who were at least 20 years old, could be soldiers, and had descended from Benjamin. They listed their names by their tribal groups and ancestral families.
\ts\*
\p
\v 38-39 Moses and Aaron counted 62, 700 men who were at least 20 years old, could be soldiers, and had descended from Dan. They listed their names by their tribal groups and ancestral families.
\ts\*
\p
\v 40-41 Moses and Aaron counted 41, 500 men who were at least 20 years old, could be soldiers, and had descended from Asher. They listed their names by their tribal groups and ancestral families.
\ts\*
\p
\v 42-43 {And} Moses and Aaron counted 53, 400 men who were at least 20 years old, could be soldiers, and had descended from Naphtali. They listed their names by their tribal groups and ancestral families.
\ts\*
\p

\c 2
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh told Moses and Aaron,
\v 2 “Israelites must set up their tents next to their own tribal flags and the emblems that represent their ancestral families. They must set up their tents at some distance around the sacred tent.
\ts\*
\v 3 Those {Israelite tribes} who set up their tents on the eastern side {of the sacred tent} must be together near the tribal flag of those who descended from Judah. {They must set up their tents} by their army divisions. Amminadab’s son Nahshon leads those who descended from Judah.
\v 4 The soldiers he leads are the 74, 600 men {from his tribe} whom you counted.
\ts\*
\v 5 The tribe that descended from Issachar must set up their tents next to {the tents of} the tribe that descended from Judah. Zuar’s son Nethanel leads the tribe that descended from Issachar.
\v 6 The soldiers he leads are the 54, 400 men {from his tribe} whom you counted.
\ts\*
\p
\v 7 The tribe that descended from Zebulun {will also set up their tents beside the tribe that descended from Judah}. Helon’s son Eliab leads those who descended from Zebulun.
\v 8 The soldiers he leads are the 57, 400 men {from his tribe} whom you counted.
\ts\*
\v 9 You counted 186, 400 men in total by their army divisions who descended from Judah and {those tribes who} set up their tents {with them}. These three tribes will start walking first {whenever the Israelites} travel to a new location.
\ts\*
\p
\v 10 {Those Israelite tribes who set up their tents} on the south side {of the sacred tent} {must be together near} the tribal flag of those who descended from Reuben. {They must set up their tents} by their army divisions. Shedeur’s son Elizur leads those who descended from Reuben.
\v 11 The soldiers he leads are the 46, 500 men {from his tribe} whom you counted.
\ts\*
\v 12 The tribe that descended from Simeon must set up their tents next to {the tents of} the tribe that descended from Reuben. Zurishaddai’s son Shelumiel leads the tribe that descended from Simeon.
\v 13 The soldiers he leads are the 59, 300 men {from his tribe} whom you counted.
\ts\*
\v 14 The tribe that descended from Gad {will also set up their tents beside the tribe that descended from Reuben}. Reuel’s son Eliasaph leads those who descended from Gad.
\v 15 The soldiers he leads are the 45, 650 men {from his tribe} whom you counted.
\ts\*
\v 16 You counted 151, 450 men in total by their army divisions who descended from Reuben and {those tribes who} set up their tents {with them}. These three tribes will start walking second {whenever the Israelites} travel to a new location.
\ts\*
\p
\v 17 {Whenever the Israelites} travel to a new location, the tribe that descended from Levi will carry the sacred tent and travel in the middle of the other tribes. The Israelites will travel in the exact same order in which they set up their tents, {and everyone will travel} in order by their tribal flags.
\ts\*
\p
\v 18 {Those Israelite tribes who set up their tents} on the west side {of the sacred tent} {must be together near} the tribal flag of those who descended from Ephraim. {They must set up their tents} by their army divisions. Ammihud’s son Elishama leads those who descended from Ephraim.
\v 19 The soldiers he leads are the 40, 500 men {from his tribe} whom you counted.
\ts\*
\v 20 The tribe that descended from Manasseh {must set up their tents} next to {the tents of} the tribe that descended from Ephraim. Pedahzur’s son Gamaliel leads the tribe that descended from Manasseh.
\v 21 The soldiers he leads are the 32, 200 men {from his tribe} whom you counted.
\ts\*
\v 22 The tribe that descended from Benjamin {will also set up their tents beside the tribe that descended from Ephraim}. Gideoni’s son Abidan leads those who descended from Benjamin.
\v 23 The soldiers he leads are the 35, 400 men {from his tribe} whom you counted.
\ts\*
\v 24 You counted 108, 100 men in total by their army divisions who descended from Ephraim and {those tribes who} set up their tents {with them}. These three tribes will start walking third {when the Israelites} move to a new location.
\v 25 {Those Israelite tribes who set up their tents} on the north side {of the sacred tent} {must be together near} the tribal flag of those who descended from Dan. {They must set up their tents} by their army divisions. Ammishaddai’s son Ahiezer leads those who descended from Dan.
\v 26 The soldiers he leads are the 62, 700 men {from his tribe} whom you counted.
\ts\*
\v 27 The tribe that descended from Asher must set up their tents next to {the tents of} the tribe that descended from Dan. Okran’s son Pagiel leads the tribe that descended from Asher.
\v 28 The soldiers he leads are the 41, 500 men {from his tribe} whom you counted.
\ts\*
\v 29 The tribe that descended from Naphtali {will also set up their tents beside the tribe that descended from Dan}. Enan’s son Ahira leads those who descended from Naphtali.
\v 30 The soldiers he leads are the 53, 400 men {from his tribe} whom you counted.
\ts\*
\v 31 You counted 157, 600 men in total who descended from Dan and {those tribes who} set up their tents {with them}. These three tribes will start walking after all the other tribes {when the Israelites} move to a new location by their tribal flags.”
\ts\*
\p
\v 32 These are the Israelites whom Moses and Aaron counted by their ancestral families. They counted 603, 550 men in total who set up their tents by their army divisions.
\v 33 However, they did not count the Levites along with the other Israelites. This is what Yahweh had ordered Moses {to do}.
\ts\*
\v 34 So the Israelites did exactly everything that Yahweh had ordered Moses {to tell them to do}. Everyone set up their tents by their own tribal flags and traveled by their tribal groups and ancestral families.
\ts\*

\c 3
\p
\v 1 Here is the list of those who had descended from Aaron and Moses when Yahweh and Moses talked on Mount Sinai.
\v 2 Aaron’s oldest son was Nadab, and his other sons were Abihu, Eleazar, and Ithamar.
\ts\*
\v 3 These are the men whom Moses appointed and ordained to minister as priests.
\v 4 However, Nadab and Abihu died in front of where Yahweh was present because they presented to him burning coals that he had not authorized. {This happened while they were} in the desert wilderness around Sinai. Nadab and Abihu did not have any sons, so Eleazar and Ithamar ministered as priests with their father Aaron {instead}.
\ts\*
\p
\v 5 Yahweh told Moses,
\v 6 “Summon the men who descended from Levi and order them to stand in front of Aaron the priest. They must help him.
\ts\*
\v 7 They are responsible to help Aaron and work for the whole {Israelite} community at the sacred tent by doing the work associated with the sacred tent.
\v 8 They must also take care of all the things in the sacred tent and work for the Israelites by doing the work associated with the sacred tent.
\ts\*
\v 9 Moses, assign those who descended from Levi to serve Aaron and those who descend from him. Out of all the Israelites, I have assigned exclusively those who descended from Levi to serve Aaron {and his family} .
\v 10 Assign Aaron and those who descend from him to do the priestly work. If anyone who is not a Levite approaches the sacred tent, the Levites must execute that person.”
\ts\*
\p
\v 11 Yahweh also told Moses,
\v 12 “Note that I indeed have appointed those who descend from Levi out of all the Israelites {to serve me} instead of {appointing} the oldest {male} from every Israelite family. So those who descend from Levi are mine
\v 13 because every firstborn {male} is mine. I consecrated the oldest male of every Israelite family and the oldest male offspring of all their farm animals when I killed every oldest {male} in Egypt. They are mine. I am Yahweh.”
\ts\*
\p
\v 14 Yahweh told Moses in the desert wilderness around Sinai,
\v 15 “Count all the males who descended from Levi and are at least one month old. {Count them} by their ancestral families and tribal groups.”
\v 16 So Moses counted all the males who descended from Levi. {He did} exactly what Yahweh ordered him {to do}.
\ts\*
\v 17 The names of Levi’s sons were Gershon, Kohath, and Merari.
\v 18 The names of Gershon’s sons by their tribal groups were Libni and Shimei.
\v 19 The {names} of Kohath’s sons by their tribal groups were Amram, Izhar, Hebron, and Uzziel.
\v 20 And the {names} of Merari’s sons by their tribal groups were Mahli and Mushi. These were the {three} tribal groups of those who descended from Levi by their ancestral families.
\ts\*
\v 21 The tribal groups that descended from Libni and Shimei were those that descended from Gershon. These were the {two} tribal groups that descended from Gershon.
\v 22 Moses counted 7, 500 males in total who were at least one month old {and had descended from Gershon}.
\v 23 The {two} tribal groups that descended from Gershon set up their tents near the back of the sacred tent on its western {side}.
\ts\*
\v 24 Lael’s son Eliasaph led the {two} tribal groups that descended from Gershon.
\v 25 At the sacred tent, those who descended from Gershon were responsible to take care of the sacred tent, including the tent {itself}, what covered it, the curtains at its entrance,
\v 26 the curtains that hang on {the fence around} the courtyard, the curtains at the entrance of the courtyard that surrounds the sacred tent and the altar, and all the braided cords that they used with these items.
\ts\*
\v 27 The tribal groups that descended from Amram, Izhar, Hebron, and Uzziel were those that descended from Kohath. These were the {four} tribal groups that descended from Kohath.
\v 28 8, 600 males in total were at least one month old {and had descended from Kohath}. {They} were responsible for taking care of the Holy Place.
\v 29 The {four} tribal groups that descended from Kohath’s sons set up their tents on the southern side of the sacred tent.
\ts\*
\v 30 Uzziel’s son Elizaphan led the {four} tribal groups that descended from Kohath.
\v 31 Those {who descended from Kohath} were responsible to take care of the sacred chest, the table, the lampstands, the altar, the items in the Holy Place that they needed to minister, the curtain {that covered the entrance of the Holy Place}, and everything that they used with these items.
\v 32 Aaron the priest’s son Eleazar led those who led those who descended from Levi. He was in charge of those who were responsible for taking care of the Holy Place.
\ts\*
\v 33 The tribal groups that descended from Mahli and Mushi were those that descended from Merari. These were the {two} tribal groups that descended from Merari.
\v 34 Moses counted 6, 200 males in total who were at least one month old {and had descended from Merari}.
\v 35 Abihail’s son Zuriel led the {two} tribal groups that descended from Merari. The {two} tribal groups set up their tents on the northern side of the sacred tent.
\ts\*
\v 36 Those who descended from Merari were in charge of taking care of the sacred tent’s wooden frame boards, poles, posts, {silver} bases, all its items, and everything that they used with these items.
\v 37 {They were} also {in charge of taking care of} the posts, bases, {bronze} pins, and braided cords {that were parts of the fence} surrounding the courtyard.
\ts\*
\v 38 Moses, Aaron, and those who descended from him set up their tents at the sacred tent on its eastern side, close to the sacred tent. {They} were responsible for taking care of the Holy Place. {In this way,} they worked for the Israelites. If anyone who was not a Levite approached the sacred tent, the Levites were to execute that person.
\v 39 Moses and Aaron counted 22, 000 males in total who were at least one month old and had descended from Levi. {Moses and Aaron counted them} by their tribal groups as Yahweh had ordered them {to do}.
\ts\*
\p
\v 40 Yahweh told Moses, “Count all the oldest males who are at least one month old in every Israelite family. List them by name.
\v 41 I am Yahweh. Reserve those who descended from Levi to {serve} me in place of the oldest males of every Israelite family. {Reserve for me} also the farm animals of those who descended from Levi in place of every Israelite farm animal’s oldest {offspring}.”
\ts\*
\v 42 So Moses counted the oldest {males} in every Israelite family. {He did} what Yahweh had ordered him {to do}.
\v 43 Moses counted by name all 22, 273 of the oldest males who are at least one month old in every Israelite family.
\ts\*
\p
\v 44 Yahweh told Moses,
\v 45 “Reserve those who descended from Levi in place of the oldest males of every Israelite family. {Reserve for me} also the farm animals of those who descended from Levi in place of every Israelite farm animal’s {oldest offspring}. I am Yahweh. Those who descended from Levi are mine.
\ts\*
\v 46 As for the money the Israelites must pay because there are 273 more firstborn Israelite males than there are males who descended from Levi,
\v 47 collect exactly five pieces {of silver} for each {of the 273 additional firstborn males}. (Use the official standard for the weight of silver that priests stored in the sacred tent, which is about 11 grams.)
\v 48 Give those {pieces of} silver to Aaron and his sons. Those {pieces} will pay for the 273 firstborn Israelite males who were more than {the males of those who descended from Levi}.”
\ts\*
\v 49 Moses collected the {pieces of} silver as payment from the {273 firstborn Israelite males} who were in addition to those for whom the Levites substituted.
\v 50 Moses collected from the oldest males of every Israelite family a total of 1, 365 {pieces of} silver according to the official standard for the weight of silver that priests stored in the sacred tent.
\v 51 Then Moses gave those {1, 365 pieces of} silver as payment to Aaron and his sons. {He did} exactly what Yahweh ordered him {to do}.
\ts\*

\c 4

\p
\v 1 Yahweh told Moses and Aaron,
\v 2 “Count the men who descended from Kohath from among those who descended from Levi. {Count them} by their tribal groups and ancestral families
\v 3 {Count only those men} who are between 30 and 50 years old, everyone who joins the group of people who work in the sacred tent.
\v 4 Those who descended from Kohath will manage the most sacred things in the sacred tent.
\ts\*
\v 5 When the Israelites move to a new location, Aaron and those who descended from him must go {to the sacred tent} and disassemble the curtain that covers {the sacred tent}. Then they must lay it over the sacred chest of the testimony.
\v 6 Then they must cover those things with fine leather, lay a completely blue covering over {that leather}, and then put its poles {in the proper place to carry it}.
\ts\*
\v 7 They must lay a blue covering over the table that is in {my} presence. Then they must place on that cloth the dishes, saucers, bowls, the jars {they use} for offering wine, and the sacred bread that they continually offer.
\v 8 Then they lay a red covering over those things, cover that covering with fine leather, and then put the table’s poles {in the proper place to carry it}.
\ts\*
\v 9 They must lay a blue covering over the lampstand that they use for making light {in the sacred tent}, its oil lamps, snuffers, trays, and all the jars containing olive oil that they use to supply oil to the lampstand.
\v 10 Then they must place the lampstand and all the items associated with it into a fine leather skin and hang all of it on the pole with which they will carry it.
\v 11 They must lay a blue covering over the golden altar, cover that covering with fine leather, and then put the altar’s poles {in the proper place to carry it}.
\ts\*
\v 12 They must place into a blue cloth all the utensils that they use to minister in the Holy Place, cover that with fine leather, and hang all of it on the pole with which they will carry it.
\v 13 They must take the ashes with {burned animal} fat from the {bronze} altar and lay a purple cloth over that altar.
\v 14 Then they must place on that cloth all the utensils that they use to minister at the bronze altar, including trays, meat forks, shovels, and bowls. Then they must cover all that with fine leather, and then put the altar’s poles {in the proper place to carry it}.
\ts\*
\v 15 When the Israelites move to a new location, Aaron and those who descended from him must finish covering the Holy Place and every item {they use in it}. Then those who descended from Kohath must carry all those things, but they must not touch {any of} the sacred items or they will die. Those are all the things associated with the sacred tent that those who descended from Kohath must carry.
\v 16 Aaron the priest’s son Eleazer is in charge of the olive oil {that the priests burn} to make light {in the sacred tent}, the spices that {they mix to} make incense, the grain offering that they continually offer, the oil {that they use} for anointing {people}, every part of the sacred tent, and everything in it, including the Holy Place and the items associated with it.”
\ts\*
\p
\v 17 Yahweh told Moses and Aaron,
\v 18 “Do not let the tribal groups that descended from Kohath die out from among those who descended from Levi.
\v 19 Rather, in order for those who descended from Kohath to stay alive when they come close to the most sacred items, Aaron and those who descended from him must enter {the Holy Place first} and tell each of those who descended from Kohath what to do and what to carry.
\v 20 Those who descended from Kohath must not look at anything in the Holy Place, not even briefly, or they will die.”
\ts\*
\p
\v 21 Yahweh told Moses,
\v 22 “Count the men who descended from Gershon as well by their ancestral families and tribal groups.
\v 23 Count all of those men who are between 30 and 50 years old. Those men will enter the sacred tent in order to minister and work there.
\ts\*
\v 24 This is what the tribal groups that descended from Gershon must do and what they must carry:
\v 25 They must carry the curtains of the sacred tent, including the tent {itself}, what covers it, the fine leather that covers over {all those things}, what covers the sacred tent’s entrance,
\v 26 the curtains that hang on {the fence} around the courtyard, the curtains at the entrance of the courtyard that surrounds the sacred tent and the altar, the braided cords, and all the utensils that they use to work {in the tent}. Those who descended from Gershon must do everything to take care of these items.
\ts\*
\v 27 Those who descended from Gershon must do all the work according to what Aaron and those who descended from him tell them to do, concerning everything that they must carry and everything that they must do. Assign them everything that they are responsible to carry.
\v 28 That is what the tribal groups who descended from Gershon must do in the sacred tent. Aaron the priest’s son Ithamar will lead them to do what they are responsible to do.
\ts\*
\p
\v 29 Moses, count those who descended from Merari by their tribal groups and ancestral families.
\v 30 Count all of those men who are between 30 and 50 years old. Those men will join the group of people who do the work associated with the sacred tent.
\ts\*
\v 31 Concerning everything that they must do in the sacred tent, these men are responsible to carry the sacred tent’s wooden frame boards, poles, posts, and {silver} bases.
\v 32 {They are also responsible to carry} the posts, bases, {bronze} pins, and braided cords {that were parts of the fence} surrounding the courtyard, all their items, and everything that they used with these items. Assign each of them by name the items that they are responsible to carry.
\ts\*
\v 33 That is everything that the families who descended from Merari must do in the sacred tent. Aaron the priest’s son Ithamar will lead them.”
\ts\*
\v 34 Moses, Aaron, and the men who lead the {Israelite} community counted the males who descended from Kohath by their tribal groups and ancestral families.
\v 35 {They counted} all of those men who were between 30 and 50 years old. Those men would join the group of people who do the work associated with the sacred tent.
\v 36 Moses and Aaron counted 2, 750 men by their tribal groups.
\ts\*
\v 37 Moses and Aaron counted these men from the tribal groups that descended from Kohath. Each one of these men works in the sacred tent. Moses and Aaron did what Yahweh had ordered them {to do} through Moses.
\ts\*
\p
\v 38 {Moses and Aaron also} counted the men who descended from Gershon by their tribal groups and ancestral families.
\v 39 {They counted} all of those men who were between 30 and 50 years old. Those men would join the group of people who do the work associated with the sacred tent.
\v 40 Moses and Aaron counted 2, 630 men by their tribal groups and ancestral families.
\ts\*
\v 41 Moses and Aaron counted these men from the tribal groups that descended from Gershon. Each one of these men works in the sacred tent. Moses and Aaron did what Yahweh ordered them {to do}.
\ts\*
\v 42 {Moses and Aaron also} counted men from the tribal groups that descended from Merari by their tribal groups and ancestral families.
\v 43 {They counted} all of those men who were between 30 and 50 years old. Those men would join the group of people who do the work associated with the sacred tent.
\v 44 Moses and Aaron counted 3, 200 men by their tribal groups.
\ts\*
\v 45 Moses and Aaron counted these men from the tribal groups that descended from Merari. Moses and Aaron did what Yahweh ordered them {to do} through Moses.
\ts\*
\v 46 Moses, Aaron, and those who led the Israelites counted all those men who descended from Levi by their tribal groups and ancestral families.
\v 47 {They counted} all of those {Levite} men who were between 30 and 50 years old. Each one of these men ministers by working in the sacred tent and by carrying it {and its items}.
\v 48 They counted a total of 8, 580 men.
\ts\*
\v 49 Moses, Aaron, and those who led the Israelites did what Yahweh had ordered them {to do} through Moses. They counted each male by what they must do {in the sacred tent} and what they must carry. These were all the men whom Yahweh had ordered Moses to count.
\ts\*

\c 5

\p
\v 1 Yahweh said to Moses,
\v 2 “Order the Israelites to remove the following people from the campgrounds: every person with a skin disease that can spread from one person to another, every person whose body discharges bodily fluid, and every person who is defiled because of dead body.
\v 3 You shall certainly remove both male and female Israelites from the campground so that they do not profane the camp, the place where I am among them.”
\v 4 The Israelites obeyed and removed those who had conditions from the campgrounds. So, the Israelites did exactly what Yahweh said to Moses.
\ts\*
\p
\v 5 Yahweh said to Moses,
\v 6 “Say this to the Israelites: ‘When any person is unfaithful to Yahweh and does anything contrary to his commands, that person is guilty.
\v 7 The guilty person shall confess his sin which he did. Then he shall pay the one against whom he sinned the full price of his sin in addition to one fifth of the full price.
\ts\*
\v 8 If there is not one whom the guilty person can pay for his sin, the guilty person will give the payment to Yahweh by giving it to the priest. In addition to this payment, the guilty person must also give a ram, which the priest shall sacrifice in order to atone for his sin.
\v 9 Every payment the Israelites give to the priest, all {of which shall be} holy, shall belong to the priest.
\v 10 Every payment a man gives shall belong to the priest. {Again,} whatever a man gives to the priest shall belong to the priest.’”
\ts\*
\p
\v 11 Yahweh said to Moses,
\v 12 “Say this to the Israelites: ‘If a man’s wife behaves unfaithfully toward her husband by having sexual relations with another man
\v 13 which her husband and no other person witnesses, which they then keep a secret from everyone so that the Israelites do not discover her sin, she is profaned.
\v 14 {If} a man develops jealous feelings and suspects his wife of sexual unfaithfulness and she has profaned herself {sexually}, or if a man develops jealous feelings and suspects his wife of sexual unfaithfulness and she has not profaned herself {sexually},
\v 15 this man shall lead his wife to the priest. He shall also bring one tenth an ephah of barley flour without pouring oil on it or placing frankincense on it, because this offering is a grain offering presented when a man is suspicious of his wife. This grain offering is {to pray that Yahweh would} remember the sin.’
\ts\*
\v 16 The priest shall call her to himself and {order} her to stand in front of Yahweh.
\v 17 The priest shall pick up the clay jar with holy water {in it}, pick up dust from the ground of the sacred tent, and he shall mix {the dust with the} holy water {in the clay jar}.
\ts\*
\v 18 The priest shall {order} the woman to stand in front of Yahweh, unbind the hair of the woman, and place in her hand the grain offering {to pray that God} remembers, which is the grain offering presented when a man suspects his wife of sexual unfaithfulness. The priest shall hold the water mixture in his hand, by which {Yahweh} will curse {the woman with a} bitter {life}.
\v 19 The priest shall order the wife to swear, and he shall say to the woman, “{Yahweh will not} curse {you with a} bitter {life with} this water mixture if you have not committed adultery nor defiled your {moral} cleanliness while married to your husband.”
\ts\*
\v 22 {Yahweh will} curse {you with} this water when it enters your stomach. It will prevent your body from bearing children.” The woman shall say, “I agree completely.”
\ts\*
\v 23 The priest shall write {the words of} these curses on a scroll, and he shall wash the ink into the water by which {Yahweh will make her life} bitter.
\ts\*
\v 24 Then, he shall order the woman to drink the water by which {Yahweh will} curse {her by making her life} bitter. She shall swallow the water by which {Yahweh will} curse {her}.
\v 25 The priest shall take from the woman’s hand the grain offering presented when a man is suspicious of his wife. He shall bring the grain offering close to the altar and dedicate it to Yahweh.
\v 26 The priest shall take a handful of the grain offering and shall {throw it} in the altar to burn it. Then, he shall order the woman to drink the water.
\ts\*
\v 27 He shall order the woman to drink the water. When the woman swallows the water by which {Yahweh curses a person with a} bitter {life}, her body will be unable to bear children, and she will become a curse in the midst of her people if she has profaned {herself sexually}, behaving unfaithfully toward her husband.
\v 28 However, if she has not profaned {herself sexually}, she is {sexually} pure, will be free {from guilt}, and will be able to bear children.
\ts\*
\v 29 These instructions are the statute of a jealous spirit: when a woman is {sexually} unfaithful to her husband and profaned,
\v 30 or when a man develops jealous feelings and suspects his wife {of sexual unfaithfulness}, the husband shall lead his wife before Yahweh, and the priest shall do to the wife everything {described in} this statute.
\ts\*
\v 31 Then, the man will be {morally} free from sin, and his wife will be {morally} guilty.’”
\ts\*
\v 20-21 The priest shall order the woman to swear the oath {where she accepts Yahweh’s} curse. The priest shall say to the woman, “However, if you have defiled {yourself sexually} while married to your husband and {if you} have profaned {yourself sexually} by having a man who is not your husband commit adultery with you, Yahweh will curse you and make you an example in the midst of your people by preventing your body from bearing children.

\c 6

\p
\v 1 Yahweh also said this to Moses:
\v 2 “Tell this to the Israelite people: If any of you wants to make a solemn promise to dedicate himself to belong to me in a special way, after you obey these instructions, you will be called a Nazir, which means ‘a dedicated person.’
\v 3 You must not drink any wine or other alcoholic drink. You must not drink grape juice or eat grapes or raisins.
\v 4 You must not eat anything that comes from grapevines, not even the skins or seeds of grapes, during the time that you are a Nazir.

\ts\*
\p
\v 5 Even your hair will be dedicated to me during the time that you are a Nazir, so you must never allow anyone to cut your hair. Until the time that your solemn promise to dedicate yourself to me is ended, you must allow your hair to grow long.

\ts\*
\v 6 And you must not go near a corpse during the time that you are a Nazir.
\v 7 Even if the person who died is your father or your mother or your brother or your sister, you must not cause yourself to become unacceptable to me by coming close to the corpse. Your long hair shows that you belong to me in a special way, so you must do what you have solemnly promised and not cut your hair.
\v 8 You are required to keep doing this all the time that you are dedicated to me in this special way.

\ts\*
\p
\v 9 If anyone dies very suddenly when he is near you, then your hair that you have dedicated to me is no longer sacred. So you must wait seven days and then shave it all off. Then you must perform a special ritual to cause yourself to become acceptable to me again.

\ts\*
\v 10 The next day you must bring two doves or two pigeons to the priest at the entrance of the sacred tent.
\v 11 The priest must kill the birds and offer them as sacrifices. One of them will be an offering to take away the guilt of your sin, and the other will be an offering that is burned completely to please me. After the priests burns them on the altar, I will forgive you for having come close to a corpse, and when your hair grows again it will be dedicated to me again.

\ts\*
\v 12 The amount of time that you were set apart for me the previous time does not count, because you had become unacceptable to me by coming close to a corpse during the time that you were a Nazir. So you must again make a solemn promise to dedicate yourself to me for the entire amount of time that you indicated the previous time. And you must also sacrifice a one year old lamb to take away your guilt.

\ts\*
\p
\v 13 When the time that you promised to dedicate yourself to me is ended, go to the entrance of the sacred tent
\v 14 and offer as sacrifices to me three animals that have no defects. Offer a one year old ram that will be burned completely, a one year old female lamb as a sacrifice to take away the guilt of your sin, and one full-grown ram as a sacrifice to restore fellowship with me.
\p
\v 15 When you bring those animals, you must also bring some wine to offer as a sacrifice. And you must also bring a basket of bread that you have made with very good flour and olive oil. But you must not put any yeast in the bread. Also brush some olive oil on some thin wafers and bring them to the priest.

\ts\*
\p
\v 16 The priest will put the young lamb and the young ram on the altar and completely burn them, in order that I will be pleased and will forgive you.
\v 17 Then he will kill the full-grown ram as an offering to restore fellowship with me, and he will also burn on the altar some of the bread and the flour and wine.

\ts\*
\p
\v 18 After that, you must stand at the entrance of the sacred tent and shave off your hair. Then you must put that hair in the fire that is under the animal that has been sacrificed on the altar to restore fellowship with me.

\ts\*
\p
\v 19 The meat from the ram’s shoulder must be boiled. After it is cooked, the priest will take it along with one of the loaves of bread and one wafer which has been brushed with olive oil, and he will put them in your hands.
\v 20 Then the priest will take them back and lift them up high to dedicate them to me. They now belong to the priest, and he is permitted to eat some of the meat from the ram’s shoulder and from its ribs and from one of its thighs, because that meat is his share of the sacrifice. After that, you will no longer be a Nazir, and you will again be permitted to drink wine.

\ts\*
\p
\v 21 Those are the regulations about the offerings that Nazir solemnly promise to bring to me to end their time of being dedicated to me. They must bring these offerings, but if they want to, they may bring additional offerings. And they must do everything that they solemnly promised to do when they dedicated themselves to me.”


\ts\*
\p
\v 22 Yahweh also said to Moses,
\v 23 “Tell Aaron and his sons that when they ask me to bless the people, they must say,
\q1 \v 24 ‘Yahweh bless you
\q2 and protect you.
\q1

\ts\*
\v 25 May he smile on you
\q2 and act kindly toward you.
\q1 \v 26 May he be good to you
\q2 and cause things to go well for you.’”
\p
\v 27 Then Yahweh said, “If Aaron and his sons ask me to bless the Israelite people, truly I will bless them.”


\ts\*

\c 7

\p
\v 1 When Moses had finished setting up the sacred tent, he poured oil on it, and set it apart for the honor of Yahweh. He also dedicated the things that are inside the sacred tent, and the altar for burning sacrifices, and all the things that would be used at the altar.
\v 2 Then the leaders of the twelve Israelite tribes, the same men who had helped Aaron and Moses to count the men who could fight in battles,
\v 3 came to the sacred tent, bringing gifts to Yahweh. They brought six sturdy carts and twelve oxen, one ox from each of the leaders and a cart from each of the two leaders.

\ts\*
\p
\v 4 Then Yahweh said to Moses,
\v 5 “Accept these gifts, in order that the descendants of Levi can use them for carrying the sacred items that are here at the sacred tent.”

\ts\*
\p
\v 6 So Moses took the carts and oxen and gave them to the descendants of Levi.
\v 7 He gave two carts and four oxen to the descendants of Gershon for their work,
\v 8 and he gave four carts and eight oxen to the descendants of Merari for their work. Aaron’s son Ithamar was the supervisor of all their work.

\ts\*
\v 9 But he did not give any carts or oxen to the descendants of Kohath, because they took care of the sacred items that were to be carried on their shoulders, not on carts.

\ts\*
\p
\v 10 On the day that the altar was dedicated, the twelve leaders brought other gifts to be dedicated and put them in front of the altar.
\v 11 Yahweh said to Moses, “On each of the next twelve days one leader should bring his gifts for the dedication of the altar.”

